{"id":"0806.4502","submitter":"Raji Heyrovska","authors":"Raji Heyrovska","title":"Atomic Structure of Benzene Which Accounts for Resonance Energy","comments":"8 pages, 2 figures; with more improvements, added dedication, more\n  references and formatted for PRL","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"physics.gen-ph physics.chem-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Benzene is a hexagonal molecule of six carbon atoms, each of which is bound\nto six hydrogen atoms. The equality of all six CC bond lengths, despite the\nalternating double and single bonds, and the surplus (resonance) energy, led to\nthe suggestion of two resonanting structures. Here, the new atomic structure\nshows that the bond length equality is due to three carbon atoms with double\nbond radii bound to three other carbon atoms with resonance bond radii (as in\ngraphene). Consequently, there are two kinds of CH bonds of slightly different\nlengths. The bond energies account for the resonance energy.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 27 Jun 2008 17:22:39 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Wed, 2 Jul 2008 12:48:06 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Wed, 9 Jul 2008 16:24:02 GMT"}],"update_date":"2008-07-09"}
